 ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_013", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Aminomethanol route (mechanistic Strecker variant)", "description": "Formaldehyde from CO\u2082 fixation condenses with NH\u2083 to form aminomethanol, the experimentally identified Strecker hemiaminal intermediate. HCN then adds to form aminoacetonitrile, which hydrolyzes to glycine. This pathway decomposes the Strecker mechanism into its individual steps.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_005"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_014", "mol_009"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_013"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_008", "description": "Formaldehyde is the central C1 hub. Produced by two independent hydrothermal routes (CO\u2082 reduction and CO FTT synthesis), it feeds into four distinct downstream pathways: Strecker synthesis, formose reaction, cyanosulfidic cyanohydrin formation, and aminomethanol condensation.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_011", "rxn_014"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_009", "description": "Aminoacetonitrile is the convergence point for all Strecker-type pathways. Produced by three independent routes: direct Strecker (rxn_004), cyanosulfidic glyconitrile amination (rxn_013), and aminomethanol + HCN (rxn_015). All converge to glycine via hydrolysis (rxn_005).", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_013", "rxn_015"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_005"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "description": "Glycolic acid is the convergence point for sugar-derived and cyanosulfidic pathways. Produced by formose-derived glycolaldehyde oxidation (rxn_007) and glyconitrile hydrolysis (rxn_012). Feeds into both direct amination to glycine (rxn_008) and glyoxylate formation (rxn_009).", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_012"], "out